[Dr. Clement is thanked for his comments.

Dr. Clement identified a major problem that these types of reports in the popular press have: a lack of clinical and often epidemiological details that are important in understanding which etiological agent is involved and how individuals acquired their infection. From the limited information published, there is no clinical description or an indication of how the soldiers might have acquired their infection. As an Army training facility, it is conceivable that both indoor instruction and outdoor field exercises took place. It would be useful to know which hantavirus is involved in these cases in Tarija department as well as other cases in that department and others. This knowledge is important for clinical management of severe cases and for knowing which rodent hosts are involved for their control (brown rat control is different from native pygmy rice rats, for example).

As Dr. Clement points out, a battery of hantavirus diagnostic agents, including SEOV antigens, is required to reach a definitive diagnosis. Ideally, every national reference diagnostic laboratory in the Americas where hantavirus infections occur should have these reagents and personnel trained in their use. Perhaps the Pan American Health Organization could coordinate such an initiative. - Mod.TY

HealthMap/ProMED map available at:
Tarija, Tarija, Bolivia: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=6438724,12643]
